What is a vitamer? Vitamers are forms of the vitamin. Thiamine that is used by cells needs to be phosphorylated â€“ that is, have one or two phosphate groups.

For species that have a long time living off of their yolk sac, most of the thiamine will be in free thiamine. Free thiamine is not readily used by organisms, but is good for storage until it is needed.

The chemical structure of free thiamine (courtesy of ChemSpider). Notice that there are no phosphate groups attached. Note about how this one is used? Is this the one used by hatcheries for supplementation?

The thiamine that is used by our bodies (and the fish) are the phosphorylated thiamines. There are two forms: thiamine monophosphate and thiamine pyrophosphate.

Thiamine monophosphate has one phosphate group attached. This vitamer of thiamine is used in some cellular processes.
Thiamine pyrophosphate (also known as thiamine diphosphate because of the two phosphate groups). This vitamer is the most readily available for use and is the most common form of thiamine in bodies.

Thiamine degrades easily when pH is basic, in the presence of UV light, and in warm temperatures. It is a water-soluble vitamin, meaning that for the most part, there is no way to store excess thiamine and anything that is not used is excreted in urine. To remain thiamine replete
